<paragraph blockId="11.[144,758,583,696]" box="[144,263,583,604]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis box="[144,263,583,604]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,758,583,696]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
The epithet refers to the 
<typeStatus box="[440,489,614,635]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">type</typeStatus>
locality Clarion Island (Revillagigedo archipelago) where the specimens of this species were collected.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[806,1422,198,403]" box="[806,918,198,219]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis box="[806,918,198,219]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[806,1422,198,403]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Dark brown (in preserved condition), encrusting to cushion-shaped sponge, with smooth surface. Consistency is cartilaginous-like, but inside is fleshy. Spicules are diods and triods, which are included in a dense collagen layer, without alveolar skeletal specialization.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[806,1422,461,696]" box="[806,935,461,482]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis box="[806,935,461,482]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[806,1422,461,696]" lastBlockId="12.[164,779,198,1046]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="266" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
Encrusting to cushion-shaped sponge from 
<quantity box="[1281,1421,491,513]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" metricValueMax="15.0" metricValueMin="2.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" unit="cm" value="0.85" valueMax="1.5" valueMin="0.2">0.2 to 1.5 cm</quantity>
in thickness, spreading between coral branches and over rocks (
<figureCitation box="[940,1027,552,574]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[144,223,1451,1470]" captionTargetBox="[271,1296,194,1422]" captionTargetId="figure-149@5.[271,1296,194,1422]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. External morphologies of plakinid species from the eastern Pacific. A, B, Plakina muricyae sp. nov. C, i, Plakina paradilopha sp. nov.; ii, Plakina muricyae sp. nov. D, Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. E, Plakortis albicans Cruz-Barraza &amp; Carballo, 2005. F, Plakinastrella clippertonensis van Soest et al., 2011." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306492" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306492/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
). The specimens cover areas up to 10 × 
<quantity box="[860,916,583,604]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" unit="cm" value="8.0">8 cm</quantity>
. Surface is uneven and rugose, with rounded bumps, which gives a granular appearance. Sponge borders in contact with the coral structures become irregular, taking the substrate’s form. Between the bumps there are small ostial pores of 330–670 μm in diameter. The surface also presents very small subectosomic canals 150–250 μm in diameter. Only one circular-shaped oscule was found, of 
<quantity box="[603,668,290,311]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in diameter. The consistency of the surface is slightly cartilaginous, but the interior is fleshy. Colour in life was not observed; in spirit it is dark and light brown on the surface and the choanosome is pale yellow.
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306502" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5306502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306502/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" startId="11.[144,223,1853,1872]" targetBox="[303,1263,742,1823]" targetPageId="11">
<paragraph blockId="11.[144,1421,1853,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[144,248,1853,1872]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Figure 5.</emphasis>
Scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy images of spicules and skeletal structure 
<emphasis bold="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis bold="true" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="265">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[295,384,1883,1902]" pageId="11" pageNumber="265" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
A, diods. B, triods. C, tangential view of the ectosome. D, transversal view of the choanosome.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,198,1046]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
Spicules: diods and triods (
<tableCitation box="[503,589,443,465]" captionStart="Table 4" captionStartId="13.[135,198,668,689]" captionText="Table 4. Comparative data for the dimensions of the spicules (in μm), locality and other characteristics of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. and Plakortis albicans, and other similar (in morphology and geography) Plakortis species for comparison. Values in parentheses are means" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Table 4</tableCitation>
). Diods are thin and elongated, typically curved in the centre, with one, two or more well-marked bent. The ends are straight with sharp or slightly rounded tips (
<figureCitation box="[570,653,534,556]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="11.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 5. Scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy images of spicules and skeletal structure of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. A, diods. B, triods. C, tangential view of the ectosome. D, transversal view of the choanosome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306502/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Fig. 5A</figureCitation>
). Diods are abundant; they measure 17.5–77.5 μm long and 1.25– 3 μm wide. Triods usually present equal angles, but can be uneven with ‘T’ or ‘Y’ shape (
<figureCitation box="[584,669,626,648]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="11.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 5. Scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy images of spicules and skeletal structure of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. A, diods. B, triods. C, tangential view of the ectosome. D, transversal view of the choanosome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306502/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Fig. 5B</figureCitation>
). Sizes of the rays are variable, 10–30 μm long (total spicule length 20–62 μm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,198,1046]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
Skeleton: the skeletal structure is formed by diods in abundance and some triods, which are included in a dense collagen layer, without alveolar or skeletal specialization and no apparent organization. The ectosome is a nondetachable pigmented layer (up to 
<quantity box="[680,744,840,862]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" unit="mm" value="1.0">1 mm</quantity>
in thickness), with dispersed diods (
<figureCitation box="[529,610,871,893]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="11.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 5. Scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy images of spicules and skeletal structure of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. A, diods. B, triods. C, tangential view of the ectosome. D, transversal view of the choanosome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306502/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Fig. 5C</figureCitation>
), and very well differentiated from the choanosome (
<figureCitation box="[596,683,901,923]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="11.[144,223,1853,1872]" captionTargetBox="[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetId="figure-196@11.[303,1263,742,1823]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figure 5. Scanning electron microscopy and light microscopy images of spicules and skeletal structure of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. A, diods. B, triods. C, tangential view of the ectosome. D, transversal view of the choanosome." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306502/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Fig. 5D</figureCitation>
). In the subectosomal area an agglomeration of spicules and pigments is present; this layer is also characterized by the presence of several canals, rather than the deep choanosome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1085,1229]" box="[164,446,1085,1106]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
<emphasis box="[164,446,1085,1106]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Ecology and distribution</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1085,1229]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
Specimens were collected in two localities from Revillagigedo archipelago: Clarion Island and Pináculo Norte (
<figureCitation box="[247,311,1177,1199]" captionStart="Figure 1" captionStartId="2.[164,243,935,954]" captionTargetBox="[294,1312,199,902]" captionTargetId="figure-428@2.[291,1315,196,905]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Figure 1. Distribution and sample localities of Plakinidae species from the Mexican Pacific coast. Numbers refer to different species as follows: 1, Plakina muricyae sp. nov.; 2, Plakina paradilopha sp. nov.; 3, Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov.; 4, Plakortis albicans Cruz-Barraza &amp; Carballo, 2005; 5, Plakinastrella clippertonensis van Soest et al., 2011." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5306490" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5306490/files/figure.png" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Specimens were found on pocilloporid coral branches and over rocks at 
<quantity box="[556,599,1208,1229]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" unit="m" value="4.0">4 m</quantity>
depth.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1269,1902]" box="[164,265,1269,1290]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
<emphasis box="[164,265,1269,1290]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Remarks</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1269,1902]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
Currently, there are three species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schulze" authorityYear="1880" box="[575,676,1299,1320]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[575,676,1299,1320]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the East Pacific coast: 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2005" box="[391,603,1330,1351]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="albicans">
<emphasis box="[391,603,1330,1351]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis albicans</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see below for remarks on this species) and 
<taxonomicName authority="(Austin, 1996)" baseAuthorityName="Austin" baseAuthorityYear="1996" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[491,683,1360,1381]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis simplex</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Austin WC" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" pagination="237 - 256" refId="ref14912" refString="Austin WC. 1996. Sponges from Rocas Alijos. In: Schmieder RM, ed. Monographiae biologicae. Rocas Alijos. Scientific results from the cordell expeditions, Vol. 75. Dordrecht: Kluwer Academic Publishers, 237 - 256." type="book chapter" year="1996">Austin, 1996</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[302,385,1391,1413]" name="Mexico" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Mexico</collectingCountry>
, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desqueyroux-Faundez &amp; van Soest" authorityYear="1997" box="[453,714,1391,1412]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[453,714,1391,1412]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the Galapagos Islands.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1269,1902]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
The species 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Austin" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[340,548,1452,1473]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="simplex">
<emphasis box="[340,548,1452,1473]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis simplex</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was originally described in the Mediterranean Sea (
<bibRefCitation author="Schulze FE" box="[563,721,1483,1505]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" pagination="407 - 451" refId="ref17084" refString="Schulze FE. 1880. Untersuchungen uber den Bau und die Entwicklung der Spongien. Neunte Mittheilung. Die Plakiniden. Zeitschrift fur wissenschaftliche Zoologie 34: 407 - 451." type="journal article" year="1880">Schulze, 1880</bibRefCitation>
) and later cited around the world. However, recent authors have discussed the conspecificity of different populations, suggesting a species complex (sibling species). Therefore, the Mexican record by 
<bibRefCitation author="Austin WC" box="[538,688,1605,1627]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" pagination="237 - 256" refId="ref14912" refString="Austin WC. 1996. Sponges from Rocas Alijos. In: Schmieder RM, ed. Monographiae biologicae. Rocas Alijos. Scientific results from the cordell expeditions, Vol. 75. Dordrecht: Kluwer Academic Publishers, 237 - 256." type="book chapter" year="1996">Austin (1996)</bibRefCitation>
is probably a different species. However, a more detailed description of this material would be necessary to confirm its taxonomic status.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[164,779,1269,1902]" lastBlockId="12.[826,1442,197,1138]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
The geographically closest species to 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[309,397,1759,1780]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desqueyroux-Faundez &amp; van Soest" authorityYear="1997" box="[434,694,1758,1779]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[434,694,1758,1779]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is different to the new species in external and internal characteristics. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desqueyroux-Faundez &amp; van Soest" authorityYear="1997" box="[418,701,1819,1840]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[418,701,1819,1840]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is an encrusting (
<quantity box="[295,357,1850,1872]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
thick), beige-coloured species whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[164,440,1880,1901]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[164,440,1880,1901]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[454,551,1881,1902]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is more cushion- shaped (up to 
<quantity box="[995,1069,197,219]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" unit="cm" value="1.5">1.5 cm</quantity>
thickness), dark brown sponge. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desqueyroux-Faundez &amp; van Soest" authorityYear="1997" box="[826,1088,228,249]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[826,1088,228,249]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presents an alveolar skeletal structure whereas 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1046,1295,259,280]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1046,1295,259,280]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1305,1392,259,280]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a dense collagen layer, without skeletal specialization. The spicules also vary in size; diods are larger and in two size categories in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Desqueyroux-Faundez &amp; van Soest" authorityYear="1997" box="[1179,1441,350,371]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis box="[1179,1441,350,371]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(126–165 by 4–8 μm and 27–92 by 1.5–4 μm) than in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[826,1064,412,433]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[826,1064,412,433]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1072,1157,412,433]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, which only presents one, smaller size category (17.5–77.5 by 1.3–3 μm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[826,1442,197,1138]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">
The species 
<taxonomicName authority="Levi, 1953" authorityName="Levi" authorityYear="1953" box="[987,1282,473,495]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis box="[987,1156,473,495]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis nigra</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Levi C" box="[1163,1282,473,495]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" pagination="853 - 855" refId="ref16489" refString="Levi C. 1953. Sur une nouvelle classification des Demosponges. Comptes rendus des seances de l'Academie des Sciences (Paris) 236: 853 - 855." type="journal article" year="1953">Lévi, 1953</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from the Red Sea and 
<taxonomicName authority="Moraes &amp; Muricy, 2003" authorityName="Moraes &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2003" box="[932,1436,503,525]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[932,1148,503,524]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis insularis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Moraes FC &amp; Muricy G" box="[1158,1436,503,525]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" pagination="1 - 13" refId="ref16518" refString="Moraes FC, Muricy G. 2003. Taxonomy of Plakortis and Plakinastrella (Demospongiae: Plakinidae) from oceanic islands off north-eastern Brazil, with description of three new species. Journal of the Marine Biological Association of the United Kingdom 83: 1 - 13." type="journal article" year="2003">Moraes &amp; Muricy, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, from north-east 
<collectingCountry box="[1019,1089,534,556]" name="Brazil" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Brazil</collectingCountry>
are the only two species possessing small diods. The rest of the known species have diods bigger than 100 μm long (see 
<tableCitation box="[1233,1318,595,617]" captionStart="Table 4" captionStartId="13.[135,198,668,689]" captionText="Table 4. Comparative data for the dimensions of the spicules (in μm), locality and other characteristics of Plakortis clarionensis sp. nov. and Plakortis albicans, and other similar (in morphology and geography) Plakortis species for comparison. Values in parentheses are means" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Table 4</tableCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Levi" authorityYear="1953" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="nigra">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis nigra</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1033,1275,626,647]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1033,1275,626,647]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1283,1368,626,647]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
in the black colour, porous surface, and because its skeletal structure is formed only by diods. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moraes &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2003" box="[1227,1441,687,708]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[1227,1441,687,708]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is encrusting, massive, rounded or flat in shape, and dark to light brown in colour. The skeleton is very similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[942,1100,779,800]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[942,1100,779,800]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">P. clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1107,1193,779,800]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, with diods and triods in low density forming a confuse structure. However, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moraes &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2003" box="[826,955,840,862]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[826,955,840,862]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">P. insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has larger diods, which always end in a sharp tip, whereas the diods in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[1194,1441,871,892]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1194,1441,871,892]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[826,915,902,923]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are smaller and end in a sharp or rounded tip. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moraes &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2003" box="[876,1094,932,953]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[876,1094,932,953]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
produces a dark brown substance when preserved, which was not observed in our specimens of 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[984,1234,993,1014]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[984,1234,993,1014]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1243,1331,993,1014]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
The consistency of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Moraes &amp; Muricy" authorityYear="2003" box="[949,1073,1024,1045]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[949,1073,1024,1045]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">P. insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is soft, compressible, and fragile, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authority="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo, 2014" authorityName="Cruz-Barraza &amp; Vega &amp; Carballo" authorityYear="2014" box="[962,1210,1055,1076]" class="Homoscleromorpha" family="Plakinidae" genus="Plakortis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Homosclerophorida" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="clarionensis" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[962,1210,1055,1076]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="266">Plakortis clarionensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1219,1305,1055,1076]" pageId="12" pageNumber="266" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
it is elastic and resistant at the surface, although the interior is fleshy.
</paragraph>
